<$transclude $tiddler="$:/plugins/rimir/doc-template/templates/page">
<$fill $name="body">

!! th-saving-tiddler hook

Used by `startup.js` to intercept tiddler renames. When a tiddler with `_canonical_uri` is saved with a different title than `draft.of`, the hook sends a synchronous XHR to the rename route and updates `_canonical_uri` on the new tiddler. The hook must return the (possibly modified) tiddler synchronously.

!! th-deleting-tiddler hook

Intercepts tiddler deletion. If the tiddler has `_canonical_uri`, shows a confirmation dialog asking whether to also delete the file on disk. If confirmed, sends an async XHR to the delete route.

!! $tw.utils.httpRequest

The `<$file-dropzone>` widget uses `$tw.utils.httpRequest` (TiddlyWiki's built-in XHR wrapper) instead of the `tm-http-request` message. This allows the widget to parse the JSON response directly and extract `canonical-uri` and `generated-uri` as variables for the `actions` callback. The `tm-http-request` message does not provide response parsing hooks.

!! ViewTemplateBodyFilter cascade

`cascade-thumbnail.tid` is tagged `$:/tags/ViewTemplateBodyFilter`. TiddlyWiki evaluates body filters in order — the first to return a non-empty result determines which body template renders the tiddler. The thumbnail cascade checks for `_thumbnail_uri` and enabled thumb-rendering config, routing matching tiddlers to `body-thumbnail.tid`.

!! module-type: route

The upload, rename, and delete JS files use `module-type: route`, which TiddlyWiki's server framework discovers at boot and registers as HTTP request handlers. Each route exports `method`, `path` (regex), and `handler`.

!! bodyFormat: "stream"

The upload route sets `bodyFormat: "stream"` to prevent TiddlyWiki's server from buffering the entire request body into memory before calling the handler. Base64-encoded files can be large, so streaming avoids default body size limits.

